**Promise vs Observable**

| | Promise | Observable |
|---|---|---|
| **Values** | Single value (or error) | Stream of 0+ values over time |
| **Eagerness** | **Eager** — executes immediately on creation | **Lazy** — executes only when subscribed |
| **Cancellation** | Not natively cancellable | Unsubscribe cancels execution |
| **Multicast** | Always shared — one resolution, many `.then()` | Unicast by default (each subscriber gets independent execution); multicast via operators |
| **Operators** | `.then()`, `.catch()`, `.finally()` | Rich operator library (map, filter, debounce, merge, switchMap, etc.) |
| **Native?** | Yes — built into JS | No — requires a library (RxJS, most commonly) |
| **Retry** | Manual | Built-in (`retry`, `retryWhen`) |

**When to use which:**

- **Promise** — single async result (HTTP request, file read, timeout). Default choice.
- **Observable** — streams of events (WebSocket messages, user input, polling, combining multiple async sources with timing control).

**Quick example:**

```js
// Promise — one value, eager
const p = new Promise(resolve => {
  console.log('runs immediately');
  resolve(42);
});

// Observable — stream, lazy
const o = new Observable(subscriber => {
  console.log('runs only on subscribe');
  subscriber.next(1);
  subscriber.next(2);
  subscriber.complete();
});
// nothing happens until:
const sub = o.subscribe(val => console.log(val));
// can cancel:
sub.unsubscribe();
```

**Key insight:** A Promise is a special case of an Observable — one that emits exactly one value and completes. You can always convert between them (`from(promise)` / `observable.toPromise()`), but Observables give you composability and cancellation that Promises lack.
